- text fields
- static text
- headings
- tables
- nested tables
- charts/graphs
- images
- frames
- subreports
- lists
- form-like elements
- lines/shapes
- floating elements
- absolute-positioned layouts

For each component type:
- list affected JRXML files
- estimate complexity
- identify accessibility risks for PDF/UA/WCAG compliance.



Analyze all JRXML files and identify accessibility risks related to PDF/UA and WCAG compliance.

Focus especially on:
- nested tables
- missing semantic heading hierarchy
- absolute positioning
- reading-order risks
- image accessibility risks
- layout tables vs semantic tables
- multi-column structures
- complex frames/subreports
- potential screen-reader issues

Classify findings as:
LOW / MEDIUM / HIGH accessibility risk.




Analyze the JRXML files and supporting Java code to identify reusable rendering patterns and common report components.

Find:
- shared table structures
- common text/header sections
- image rendering patterns
- reusable subreports
- common styles
- common layout templates

Suggest which components should be converted into accessibility-safe reusable generators.




Analyze all JRXML files and identify potential heading structures based on:
- font size
- bold styling
- positioning
- repeated section patterns

Suggest probable H1/H2/H3 semantic hierarchy mappings for accessible PDF generation.




Analyze JRXML layouts for potential reading-order problems in accessible PDF generation.

Focus on:
- side-by-side elements
- floating elements
- nested frames
- overlapping components
- absolute positioning
- subreports
- multi-column layouts

Explain which layouts may confuse screen readers.




Suggest an accessibility-first redesign strategy for these JRXML reports while minimizing visual changes.

Recommend:
- semantic heading hierarchy
- simplified layouts
- reduced nested table usage
- accessibility-safe reusable components
- logical reading order improvements
- tagged PDF best practices.
